⸻

🔎 Get Last Shutdown Time + Reason

This is what real ops teams use.

journalctl -u filebeat --since "1 day ago"

To see last stop:

journalctl -u filebeat | grep "Stopped"

To see crash reason:

journalctl -u filebeat -n 100

If killed by system (OOM):

You’ll see:

Killed process XXXX (filebeat) out of memory

Check:

dmesg | grep -i kill


⸻

🕒 Get Exact Last Restart Timestamp

systemctl show filebeat --property=ActiveEnterTimestamp

Last exit timestamp:

systemctl show filebeat --property=InactiveEnterTimestamp


⸻

📁 Ensure Log Path Exists

Create log directories properly:

sudo mkdir -p /var/log/filebeat
sudo mkdir -p /var/log/metricbeat
sudo chown -R root:root /var/log/filebeat
sudo chown -R root:root /var/log/metricbeat


⸻

🔥 Optional: Custom Wrapper Script (Advanced Ops)

If you want one command showing:
	•	status
	•	last shutdown
	•	memory usage
	•	log path
	•	error count

Create:

sudo nano /usr/local/bin/beats-status

Add:

#!/bin/bash
echo "===== FILEBEAT STATUS ====="
systemctl status filebeat --no-pager | head -n 10
echo ""
echo "Last Shutdown:"
systemctl show filebeat --property=InactiveEnterTimestamp
echo ""
echo "Recent Errors:"
journalctl -u filebeat -n 20 | grep -i error
echo ""
echo "Log Path: /var/log/filebeat/"

Make executable:

chmod +x /usr/local/bin/beats-status

Run:

beats-status


